{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":1000,"text":"Suppose that two American friends are traveling together in Italy."},{"time":4000,"text":"They go to see Michelangelo's \"David,\""},{"time":6000,"text":"and when they finally come face to face with the statue,"},{"time":8000,"text":"they both freeze dead in their tracks."},{"time":10000,"text":"The first guy -- we'll call him Adam --"},{"time":12000,"text":"is transfixed by the beauty of the perfect human form."},{"time":15000,"text":"The second guy -- we'll call him Bill --"},{"time":17000,"text":"is transfixed by embarrassment, at staring at the thing there in the center."},{"time":22000,"text":"So here's my question for you:"},{"time":24000,"text":"which one of these two guys was more likely to have voted for George Bush,"},{"time":28000,"text":"which for Al Gore?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":30000,"text":"I don't need a show of hands"},{"time":31000,"text":"because we all have the same political stereotypes."},{"time":34000,"text":"We all know that it's Bill."},{"time":36000,"text":"And in this case, the stereotype corresponds to reality."},{"time":40000,"text":"It really is a fact that liberals are much higher than conservatives"},{"time":43000,"text":"on a major personality trait called openness to experience."},{"time":46000,"text":"People who are high in openness to experience"},{"time":48000,"text":"just crave novelty, variety, diversity, new ideas, travel."},{"time":52000,"text":"People low on it like things that are familiar, that are safe and dependable."}]},{"cues":[{"time":57000,"text":"If you know about this trait,"},{"time":59000,"text":"you can understand a lot of puzzles about human behavior."},{"time":61000,"text":"You can understand why artists are so different from accountants."},{"time":64000,"text":"You can actually predict what kinds of books they like to read,"},{"time":66000,"text":"what kinds of places they like to travel to,"},{"time":68000,"text":"and what kinds of food they like to eat."},{"time":70000,"text":"Once you understand this trait, you can understand"},{"time":73000,"text":"why anybody would eat at Applebee's, but not anybody that you know."},{"time":77000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":83000,"text":"This trait also tells us a lot about politics."},{"time":85000,"text":"The main researcher of this trait, Robert McCrae says that,"},{"time":88000,"text":"\"Open individuals have an affinity for liberal, progressive, left-wing political views\" --"},{"time":92000,"text":"they like a society which is open and changing --"},{"time":94000,"text":"\"whereas closed individuals prefer conservative, traditional, right-wing views.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":99000,"text":"This trait also tells us a lot about the kinds of groups people join."},{"time":103000,"text":"So here's the description of a group I found on the Web."},{"time":105000,"text":"What kinds of people would join a global community"},{"time":107000,"text":"welcoming people from every discipline and culture,"},{"time":109000,"text":"who seek a deeper understanding of the world,"},{"time":111000,"text":"and who hope to turn that understanding into a better future for us all?"},{"time":114000,"text":"This is from some guy named Ted."},{"time":116000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":118000,"text":"Well, let's see now, if openness predicts who becomes liberal,"},{"time":122000,"text":"and openness predicts who becomes a TEDster,"},{"time":124000,"text":"then might we predict that most TEDsters are liberal?"},{"time":127000,"text":"Let's find out."},{"time":128000,"text":"I'm going to ask you to raise your hand, whether you are liberal, left of center --"},{"time":132000,"text":"on social issues, we're talking about, primarily --"},{"time":134000,"text":"or conservative, and I'll give a third option,"},{"time":136000,"text":"because I know there are a number of libertarians in the audience."},{"time":138000,"text":"So, right now, please raise your hand --"},{"time":140000,"text":"down in the simulcast rooms, too,"},{"time":141000,"text":"let's let everybody see who's here --"},{"time":143000,"text":"please raise your hand if you would say that you are liberal or left of center."},{"time":146000,"text":"Please raise your hand high right now. OK."},{"time":150000,"text":"Please raise your hand if you'd say you're libertarian."},{"time":153000,"text":"OK, about a -- two dozen."},{"time":155000,"text":"And please raise your hand if you'd say you are right of center or conservative."},{"time":158000,"text":"One, two, three, four, five -- about eight or 10."}]},{"cues":[{"time":164000,"text":"OK. This is a bit of a problem."},{"time":167000,"text":"Because if our goal is to understand the world,"},{"time":170000,"text":"to seek a deeper understanding of the world,"},{"time":172000,"text":"our general lack of moral diversity here is going to make it harder."},{"time":175000,"text":"Because when people all share values, when people all share morals,"},{"time":179000,"text":"they become a team, and once you engage the psychology of teams,"},{"time":182000,"text":"it shuts down open-minded thinking."},{"time":187000,"text":"When the liberal team loses, as it did in 2004,"},{"time":191000,"text":"and as it almost did in 2000, we comfort ourselves."},{"time":195000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":197000,"text":"We try to explain why half of America voted for the other team."},{"time":201000,"text":"We think they must be blinded by religion, or by simple stupidity."},{"time":206000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":209000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":217000,"text":"So, if you think that half of America votes Republican"},{"time":223000,"text":"because they are blinded in this way,"},{"time":226000,"text":"then my message to you is that you're trapped in a moral matrix,"},{"time":229000,"text":"in a particular moral matrix."},{"time":230000,"text":"And by the matrix, I mean literally the matrix, like the movie \"The Matrix.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":234000,"text":"But I'm here today to give you a choice."},{"time":236000,"text":"You can either take the blue pill and stick to your comforting delusions,"},{"time":240000,"text":"or you can take the red pill,"},{"time":242000,"text":"learn some moral psychology and step outside the moral matrix."},{"time":245000,"text":"Now, because I know --"},{"time":247000,"text":"(Applause) --"},{"time":250000,"text":"OK, I assume that answers my question."},{"time":252000,"text":"I was going to ask you which one you picked, but no need."},{"time":254000,"text":"You're all high in openness to experience, and besides,"},{"time":256000,"text":"it looks like it might even taste good, and you're all epicures."},{"time":259000,"text":"So anyway, let's go with the red pill."},{"time":261000,"text":"Let's study some moral psychology and see where it takes us."}]},{"cues":[{"time":263000,"text":"Let's start at the beginning."},{"time":265000,"text":"What is morality and where does it come from?"},{"time":267000,"text":"The worst idea in all of psychology"},{"time":269000,"text":"is the idea that the mind is a blank slate at birth."},{"time":272000,"text":"Developmental psychology has shown"},{"time":274000,"text":"that kids come into the world already knowing so much"},{"time":276000,"text":"about the physical and social worlds,"},{"time":278000,"text":"and programmed to make it really easy for them to learn certain things"},{"time":282000,"text":"and hard to learn others."},{"time":283000,"text":"The best definition of innateness I've ever seen --"},{"time":285000,"text":"this just clarifies so many things for me --"},{"time":287000,"text":"is from the brain scientist Gary Marcus."},{"time":289000,"text":"He says, \"The initial organization of the brain does not depend that much on experience."},{"time":294000,"text":"Nature provides a first draft, which experience then revises."},{"time":297000,"text":"Built-in doesn't mean unmalleable;"},{"time":299000,"text":"it means organized in advance of experience.\""},{"time":302000,"text":"OK, so what's on the first draft of the moral mind?"},{"time":304000,"text":"To find out, my colleague, Craig Joseph, and I"},{"time":307000,"text":"read through the literature on anthropology,"},{"time":309000,"text":"on culture variation in morality"},{"time":311000,"text":"and also on evolutionary psychology, looking for matches."},{"time":313000,"text":"What are the sorts of things that people talk about across disciplines?"},{"time":316000,"text":"That you find across cultures and even across species?"},{"time":318000,"text":"We found five -- five best matches,"},{"time":320000,"text":"which we call the five foundations of morality."}]},{"cues":[{"time":322000,"text":"The first one is harm/care."},{"time":324000,"text":"We're all mammals here, we all have a lot of neural and hormonal programming"},{"time":328000,"text":"that makes us really bond with others, care for others,"},{"time":330000,"text":"feel compassion for others, especially the weak and vulnerable."},{"time":333000,"text":"It gives us very strong feelings about those who cause harm."},{"time":336000,"text":"This moral foundation underlies about 70 percent"},{"time":339000,"text":"of the moral statements I've heard here at TED."}]},{"cues":[{"time":341000,"text":"The second foundation is fairness/reciprocity."},{"time":344000,"text":"There's actually ambiguous evidence"},{"time":346000,"text":"as to whether you find reciprocity in other animals,"},{"time":348000,"text":"but the evidence for people could not be clearer."},{"time":350000,"text":"This Norman Rockwell painting is called \"The Golden Rule,\""},{"time":352000,"text":"and we heard about this from Karen Armstrong, of course,"},{"time":354000,"text":"as the foundation of so many religions."},{"time":357000,"text":"That second foundation underlies the other 30 percent"},{"time":359000,"text":"of the moral statements I've heard here at TED."}]},{"cues":[{"time":361000,"text":"The third foundation is in-group/loyalty."},{"time":363000,"text":"You do find groups in the animal kingdom --"},{"time":365000,"text":"you do find cooperative groups --"},{"time":367000,"text":"but these groups are always either very small or they're all siblings."},{"time":370000,"text":"It's only among humans that you find very large groups of people"},{"time":373000,"text":"who are able to cooperate, join together into groups,"},{"time":376000,"text":"but in this case, groups that are united to fight other groups."},{"time":380000,"text":"This probably comes from our long history of tribal living, of tribal psychology."},{"time":384000,"text":"And this tribal psychology is so deeply pleasurable"},{"time":386000,"text":"that even when we don't have tribes,"},{"time":388000,"text":"we go ahead and make them, because it's fun."},{"time":391000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":394000,"text":"Sports is to war as pornography is to sex."},{"time":397000,"text":"We get to exercise some ancient, ancient drives."}]},{"cues":[{"time":400000,"text":"The fourth foundation is authority/respect."},{"time":403000,"text":"Here you see submissive gestures from two members of very closely related species."},{"time":406000,"text":"But authority in humans is not so closely based on power and brutality,"},{"time":410000,"text":"as it is in other primates."},{"time":412000,"text":"It's based on more voluntary deference,"},{"time":414000,"text":"and even elements of love, at times."}]},{"cues":[{"time":416000,"text":"The fifth foundation is purity/sanctity."},{"time":418000,"text":"This painting is called \"The Allegory Of Chastity,\""},{"time":421000,"text":"but purity's not just about suppressing female sexuality."},{"time":424000,"text":"It's about any kind of ideology, any kind of idea"},{"time":427000,"text":"that tells you that you can attain virtue"},{"time":429000,"text":"by controlling what you do with your body,"},{"time":430000,"text":"by controlling what you put into your body."},{"time":432000,"text":"And while the political right may moralize sex much more,"},{"time":436000,"text":"the political left is really doing a lot of it with food."},{"time":438000,"text":"Food is becoming extremely moralized nowadays,"},{"time":440000,"text":"and a lot of it is ideas about purity,"},{"time":442000,"text":"about what you're willing to touch, or put into your body."}]},{"cues":[{"time":445000,"text":"I believe these are the five best candidates"},{"time":448000,"text":"for what's written on the first draft of the moral mind."},{"time":450000,"text":"I think this is what we come with, at least"},{"time":451000,"text":"a preparedness to learn all of these things."},{"time":454000,"text":"But as my son, Max, grows up in a liberal college town,"},{"time":458000,"text":"how is this first draft going to get revised?"},{"time":460000,"text":"And how will it end up being different"},{"time":462000,"text":"from a kid born 60 miles south of us in Lynchburg, Virginia?"},{"time":465000,"text":"To think about culture variation, let's try a different metaphor."},{"time":467000,"text":"If there really are five systems at work in the mind --"},{"time":470000,"text":"five sources of intuitions and emotions --"},{"time":472000,"text":"then we can think of the moral mind"},{"time":474000,"text":"as being like one of those audio equalizers that has five channels,"},{"time":476000,"text":"where you can set it to a different setting on every channel."},{"time":478000,"text":"And my colleagues, Brian Nosek and Jesse Graham, and I,"},{"time":481000,"text":"made a questionnaire, which we put up on the Web at www.YourMorals.org."},{"time":486000,"text":"And so far, 30,000 people have taken this questionnaire, and you can too."},{"time":491000,"text":"Here are the results."},{"time":492000,"text":"Here are the results from about 23,000 American citizens."},{"time":495000,"text":"On the left, I've plotted the scores for liberals;"},{"time":497000,"text":"on the right, those for conservatives; in the middle, the moderates."},{"time":499000,"text":"The blue line shows you people's responses"},{"time":501000,"text":"on the average of all the harm questions."}]},{"cues":[{"time":503000,"text":"So, as you see, people care about harm and care issues."},{"time":506000,"text":"They give high endorsement of these sorts of statements"},{"time":508000,"text":"all across the board, but as you also see,"},{"time":510000,"text":"liberals care about it a little more than conservatives -- the line slopes down."},{"time":513000,"text":"Same story for fairness."},{"time":515000,"text":"But look at the other three lines."},{"time":517000,"text":"For liberals, the scores are very low."},{"time":519000,"text":"Liberals are basically saying, \"No, this is not morality."},{"time":521000,"text":"In-group, authority, purity -- this stuff has nothing to do with morality. I reject it.\""},{"time":524000,"text":"But as people get more conservative, the values rise."},{"time":526000,"text":"We can say that liberals have a kind of a two-channel,"},{"time":529000,"text":"or two-foundation morality."},{"time":530000,"text":"Conservatives have more of a five-foundation,"},{"time":532000,"text":"or five-channel morality."}]},{"cues":[{"time":534000,"text":"We find this in every country we look at."},{"time":535000,"text":"Here's the data for 1,100 Canadians."},{"time":537000,"text":"I'll just flip through a few other slides."},{"time":539000,"text":"The U.K., Australia, New Zealand, Western Europe, Eastern Europe,"},{"time":542000,"text":"Latin America, the Middle East, East Asia and South Asia."},{"time":546000,"text":"Notice also that on all of these graphs,"},{"time":548000,"text":"the slope is steeper on in-group, authority, purity."},{"time":551000,"text":"Which shows that within any country,"},{"time":553000,"text":"the disagreement isn't over harm and fairness."},{"time":556000,"text":"Everybody -- I mean, we debate over what's fair --"},{"time":558000,"text":"but everybody agrees that harm and fairness matter."},{"time":561000,"text":"Moral arguments within cultures"},{"time":563000,"text":"are especially about issues of in-group, authority, purity."}]},{"cues":[{"time":566000,"text":"This effect is so robust that we find it no matter how we ask the question."},{"time":569000,"text":"In one recent study,"},{"time":571000,"text":"we asked people to suppose you're about to get a dog."},{"time":573000,"text":"You picked a particular breed,"},{"time":574000,"text":"you learned some new information about the breed."},{"time":576000,"text":"Suppose you learn that this particular breed is independent-minded,"},{"time":579000,"text":"and relates to its owner as a friend and an equal?"},{"time":581000,"text":"Well, if you are a liberal, you say, \"Hey, that's great!\""},{"time":583000,"text":"Because liberals like to say, \"Fetch, please.\""},{"time":585000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":590000,"text":"But if you're conservative, that's not so attractive."},{"time":593000,"text":"If you're conservative, and you learn that a dog's extremely loyal"},{"time":596000,"text":"to its home and family, and doesn't warm up quickly to strangers,"},{"time":598000,"text":"for conservatives, well, loyalty is good -- dogs ought to be loyal."},{"time":601000,"text":"But to a liberal, it sounds like this dog"},{"time":603000,"text":"is running for the Republican nomination."},{"time":605000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":606000,"text":"So, you might say, OK,"},{"time":608000,"text":"there are these differences between liberals and conservatives,"},{"time":610000,"text":"but what makes those three other foundations moral?"},{"time":612000,"text":"Aren't those just the foundations of xenophobia"},{"time":614000,"text":"and authoritarianism and Puritanism?"},{"time":616000,"text":"What makes them moral?"},{"time":617000,"text":"The answer, I think, is contained in this incredible triptych from Hieronymus Bosch,"},{"time":620000,"text":"\"The Garden of Earthly Delights.\""},{"time":622000,"text":"In the first panel, we see the moment of creation."},{"time":625000,"text":"All is ordered, all is beautiful, all the people and animals"},{"time":629000,"text":"are doing what they're supposed to be doing, where they're supposed to be."},{"time":632000,"text":"But then, given the way of the world, things change."},{"time":635000,"text":"We get every person doing whatever he wants,"},{"time":637000,"text":"with every aperture of every other person and every other animal."},{"time":640000,"text":"Some of you might recognize this as the '60s."},{"time":642000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":643000,"text":"But the '60s inevitably gives way to the '70s,"},{"time":647000,"text":"where the cuttings of the apertures hurt a little bit more."},{"time":651000,"text":"Of course, Bosch called this hell."}]},{"cues":[{"time":653000,"text":"So this triptych, these three panels"},{"time":656000,"text":"portray the timeless truth that order tends to decay."},{"time":661000,"text":"The truth of social entropy."},{"time":663000,"text":"But lest you think this is just some part of the Christian imagination"},{"time":666000,"text":"where Christians have this weird problem with pleasure,"},{"time":668000,"text":"here's the same story, the same progression,"},{"time":671000,"text":"told in a paper that was published in Nature a few years ago,"},{"time":674000,"text":"in which Ernst Fehr and Simon Gachter had people play a commons dilemma."},{"time":678000,"text":"A game in which you give people money,"},{"time":680000,"text":"and then, on each round of the game,"},{"time":682000,"text":"they can put money into a common pot,"},{"time":684000,"text":"and then the experimenter doubles what's in there,"},{"time":686000,"text":"and then it's all divided among the players."},{"time":688000,"text":"So it's a really nice analog for all sorts of environmental issues,"},{"time":691000,"text":"where we're asking people to make a sacrifice"},{"time":693000,"text":"and they themselves don't really benefit from their own sacrifice."},{"time":695000,"text":"But you really want everybody else to sacrifice,"},{"time":697000,"text":"but everybody has a temptation to a free ride."},{"time":699000,"text":"And what happens is that, at first, people start off reasonably cooperative --"},{"time":703000,"text":"and this is all played anonymously."},{"time":705000,"text":"On the first round, people give about half of the money that they can."},{"time":708000,"text":"But they quickly see, \"You know what, other people aren't doing so much though."},{"time":711000,"text":"I don't want to be a sucker. I'm not going to cooperate.\""},{"time":713000,"text":"And so cooperation quickly decays from reasonably good, down to close to zero."}]},{"cues":[{"time":717000,"text":"But then -- and here's the trick --"},{"time":719000,"text":"Fehr and Gachter said, on the seventh round, they told people,"},{"time":721000,"text":"\"You know what? New rule."},{"time":723000,"text":"If you want to give some of your own money"},{"time":725000,"text":"to punish people who aren't contributing, you can do that.\""},{"time":729000,"text":"And as soon as people heard about the punishment issue going on,"},{"time":732000,"text":"cooperation shoots up."},{"time":734000,"text":"It shoots up and it keeps going up."},{"time":736000,"text":"There's a lot of research showing that to solve cooperative problems, it really helps."},{"time":739000,"text":"It's not enough to just appeal to people's good motives."},{"time":741000,"text":"It really helps to have some sort of punishment."},{"time":743000,"text":"Even if it's just shame or embarrassment or gossip,"},{"time":745000,"text":"you need some sort of punishment to bring people,"},{"time":748000,"text":"when they're in large groups, to cooperate."},{"time":750000,"text":"There's even some recent research suggesting that religion --"},{"time":753000,"text":"priming God, making people think about God --"},{"time":755000,"text":"often, in some situations, leads to more cooperative, more pro-social behavior."}]},{"cues":[{"time":761000,"text":"Some people think that religion is an adaptation"},{"time":763000,"text":"evolved both by cultural and biological evolution"},{"time":765000,"text":"to make groups to cohere,"},{"time":767000,"text":"in part for the purpose of trusting each other,"},{"time":769000,"text":"and then being more effective at competing with other groups."},{"time":771000,"text":"I think that's probably right,"},{"time":772000,"text":"although this is a controversial issue."},{"time":774000,"text":"But I'm particularly interested in religion,"},{"time":776000,"text":"and the origin of religion, and in what it does to us and for us."},{"time":779000,"text":"Because I think that the greatest wonder in the world is not the Grand Canyon."},{"time":783000,"text":"The Grand Canyon is really simple."},{"time":785000,"text":"It's just a lot of rock, and then a lot of water and wind, and a lot of time,"},{"time":788000,"text":"and you get the Grand Canyon."},{"time":790000,"text":"It's not that complicated."},{"time":791000,"text":"This is what's really complicated,"},{"time":793000,"text":"that there were people living in places like the Grand Canyon,"},{"time":795000,"text":"cooperating with each other, or on the savannahs of Africa,"},{"time":797000,"text":"or on the frozen shores of Alaska, and then some of these villages"},{"time":800000,"text":"grew into the mighty cities of Babylon, and Rome, and Tenochtitlan."},{"time":804000,"text":"How did this happen?"},{"time":805000,"text":"This is an absolute miracle, much harder to explain than the Grand Canyon."}]},{"cues":[{"time":808000,"text":"The answer, I think, is that they used every tool in the toolbox."},{"time":811000,"text":"It took all of our moral psychology"},{"time":813000,"text":"to create these cooperative groups."},{"time":815000,"text":"Yes, you do need to be concerned about harm,"},{"time":817000,"text":"you do need a psychology of justice."},{"time":818000,"text":"But it really helps to organize a group if you can have sub-groups,"},{"time":821000,"text":"and if those sub-groups have some internal structure,"},{"time":824000,"text":"and if you have some ideology that tells people"},{"time":826000,"text":"to suppress their carnality, to pursue higher, nobler ends."},{"time":830000,"text":"And now we get to the crux of the disagreement"},{"time":832000,"text":"between liberals and conservatives."},{"time":834000,"text":"Because liberals reject three of these foundations."},{"time":836000,"text":"They say \"No, let's celebrate diversity, not common in-group membership.\""},{"time":839000,"text":"They say, \"Let's question authority.\""},{"time":841000,"text":"And they say, \"Keep your laws off my body.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":843000,"text":"Liberals have very noble motives for doing this."},{"time":846000,"text":"Traditional authority, traditional morality can be quite repressive,"},{"time":849000,"text":"and restrictive to those at the bottom, to women, to people that don't fit in."},{"time":852000,"text":"So liberals speak for the weak and oppressed."},{"time":854000,"text":"They want change and justice, even at the risk of chaos."},{"time":856000,"text":"This guy's shirt says, \"Stop bitching, start a revolution.\""},{"time":859000,"text":"If you're high in openness to experience, revolution is good,"},{"time":861000,"text":"it's change, it's fun."},{"time":863000,"text":"Conservatives, on the other hand, speak for institutions and traditions."},{"time":866000,"text":"They want order, even at some cost to those at the bottom."},{"time":870000,"text":"The great conservative insight is that order is really hard to achieve."},{"time":872000,"text":"It's really precious, and it's really easy to lose."},{"time":875000,"text":"So as Edmund Burke said, \"The restraints on men,"},{"time":877000,"text":"as well as their liberties, are to be reckoned among their rights.\""},{"time":880000,"text":"This was after the chaos of the French Revolution."},{"time":882000,"text":"So once you see this -- once you see"},{"time":884000,"text":"that liberals and conservatives both have something to contribute,"},{"time":887000,"text":"that they form a balance on change versus stability --"},{"time":890000,"text":"then I think the way is open to step outside the moral matrix."}]},{"cues":[{"time":893000,"text":"This is the great insight that all the Asian religions have attained."},{"time":898000,"text":"Think about yin and yang."},{"time":900000,"text":"Yin and yang aren't enemies. Yin and yang don't hate each other."},{"time":902000,"text":"Yin and yang are both necessary, like night and day,"},{"time":904000,"text":"for the functioning of the world."},{"time":906000,"text":"You find the same thing in Hinduism."},{"time":908000,"text":"There are many high gods in Hinduism."},{"time":910000,"text":"Two of them are Vishnu, the preserver, and Shiva, the destroyer."},{"time":913000,"text":"This image actually is both of those gods sharing the same body."},{"time":916000,"text":"You have the markings of Vishnu on the left,"},{"time":918000,"text":"so we could think of Vishnu as the conservative god."},{"time":921000,"text":"You have the markings of Shiva on the right,"},{"time":923000,"text":"Shiva's the liberal god. And they work together."},{"time":925000,"text":"You find the same thing in Buddhism."},{"time":927000,"text":"These two stanzas contain, I think, the deepest insights"},{"time":929000,"text":"that have ever been attained into moral psychology."},{"time":932000,"text":"From the Zen master Seng-ts'an:"},{"time":934000,"text":"\"If you want the truth to stand clear before you, never be for or against."},{"time":938000,"text":"The struggle between for and against is the mind's worst disease.\""},{"time":942000,"text":"Now unfortunately, it's a disease"},{"time":944000,"text":"that has been caught by many of the world's leaders."},{"time":946000,"text":"But before you feel superior to George Bush,"},{"time":949000,"text":"before you throw a stone, ask yourself, do you accept this?"},{"time":953000,"text":"Do you accept stepping out of the battle of good and evil?"},{"time":956000,"text":"Can you be not for or against anything?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":960000,"text":"So, what's the point? What should you do?"},{"time":963000,"text":"Well, if you take the greatest insights"},{"time":965000,"text":"from ancient Asian philosophies and religions,"},{"time":967000,"text":"and you combine them with the latest research on moral psychology,"},{"time":969000,"text":"I think you come to these conclusions:"},{"time":971000,"text":"that our righteous minds were designed by evolution"},{"time":975000,"text":"to unite us into teams, to divide us against other teams"},{"time":978000,"text":"and then to blind us to the truth."},{"time":981000,"text":"So what should you do? Am I telling you to not strive?"},{"time":985000,"text":"Am I telling you to embrace Seng-ts'an and stop,"},{"time":988000,"text":"stop with this struggle of for and against?"},{"time":991000,"text":"No, absolutely not. I'm not saying that."},{"time":993000,"text":"This is an amazing group of people who are doing so much,"},{"time":996000,"text":"using so much of their talent, their brilliance, their energy, their money,"},{"time":1000000,"text":"to make the world a better place, to fight --"},{"time":1002000,"text":"to fight wrongs, to solve problems."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1006000,"text":"But as we learned from Samantha Power, in her story"},{"time":1010000,"text":"about Sergio Vieira de Mello, you can't just go charging in,"},{"time":1015000,"text":"saying, \"You're wrong, and I'm right.\""},{"time":1017000,"text":"Because, as we just heard, everybody thinks they are right."},{"time":1021000,"text":"A lot of the problems we have to solve"},{"time":1023000,"text":"are problems that require us to change other people."},{"time":1026000,"text":"And if you want to change other people, a much better way to do it"},{"time":1029000,"text":"is to first understand who we are -- understand our moral psychology,"},{"time":1033000,"text":"understand that we all think we're right -- and then step out,"},{"time":1036000,"text":"even if it's just for a moment, step out -- check in with Seng-ts'an."},{"time":1040000,"text":"Step out of the moral matrix,"},{"time":1042000,"text":"just try to see it as a struggle playing out,"},{"time":1044000,"text":"in which everybody does think they're right,"},{"time":1046000,"text":"and everybody, at least, has some reasons -- even if you disagree with them --"},{"time":1048000,"text":"everybody has some reasons for what they're doing."},{"time":1050000,"text":"Step out."},{"time":1051000,"text":"And if you do that, that's the essential move to cultivate moral humility,"},{"time":1055000,"text":"to get yourself out of this self-righteousness,"},{"time":1056000,"text":"which is the normal human condition."},{"time":1058000,"text":"Think about the Dalai Lama."},{"time":1060000,"text":"Think about the enormous moral authority of the Dalai Lama --"},{"time":1063000,"text":"and it comes from his moral humility."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1067000,"text":"So I think the point -- the point of my talk,"},{"time":1069000,"text":"and I think the point of TED --"},{"time":1072000,"text":"is that this is a group that is passionately engaged"},{"time":1075000,"text":"in the pursuit of changing the world for the better."},{"time":1077000,"text":"People here are passionately engaged"},{"time":1080000,"text":"in trying to make the world a better place."},{"time":1082000,"text":"But there is also a passionate commitment to the truth."},{"time":1085000,"text":"And so I think that the answer is to use that passionate commitment"},{"time":1089000,"text":"to the truth to try to turn it into a better future for us all."},{"time":1093000,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":1094000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}